04410nam a22006015i 9781479845286DE-B159720200608045044.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200608t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798452867 a10.18574/97814798452862doi  a(DE-B1597)548406  a(OCoLC)1014019160  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF4945b.R53 2018 7aPOL0280002bisacsh04a320.609732231 aRiccucci, Norma M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolicy Drift :bShared Powers and the Making of U.S. Law and Policy /cNorma M. Riccucci. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Making of Law, Policy, and Policy Drifts -- t2. Privacy Rights and U.S. Surveillance Policy Drifts -- t3. Civil Rights Law and Policy Drifts -- t4. The Politics of Climate Control Policy Drifts -- t5. Conclusions -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe role of formal and informal institutional forces in changing three areas of U.S. public policy: privacy rights, civil rights and climate policyThere is no finality to the public policy process. Although it's often assumed that once a law is enacted it is implemented faithfully, even policies believed to be stable can change or drift in unexpected directions. The Fourth Amendment, for example, guarantees Americans' privacy rights, but the 9/11 terrorist attacks set off one of the worst cases of government-sponsored espionage. Policy changes instituted by the National Security Agency led to widespread warrantless surveillance, a drift in public policy that led to lawsuits challenging the constitutionality of wiretapping the American people. Much of the research in recent decades ignores the impact of large-scale, slow-moving, secular forces in political, social, and economic environments on public policy. In Policy Drift, Norma Riccucci sheds light on how institutional forces collectively contributed to major change in three key areas of U.S. policy (privacy rights, civil rights, and climate policy) without any new policy explicitly being written. Formal levers of change-U.S. Supreme Court decisions; inaction by Congress; Presidential executive orders-stimulated by social, political or economic forces, organized permutations which ultimately shaped and defined contemporary public policy.Invariably, implementations of new policies are embedded within a political landscape. Political actors, motivated by social and economic factors, may explicitly employ strategies to shift the direction of existing public polices or derail them altogether. Some segments of the population will benefit from this process, while others will not; thus, "policy drifts" carry significant consequences for social and economic change. A comprehensive account of inadvertent changes to privacy rights, civil rights, and climate policy, Policy Drift demonstrates how unanticipated levers of change can modify the status quo in public policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aLawxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aLegislationzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479845286423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479845286.jpg  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK